Firefighters defend property from a bushfire at Hillville near Taree, 350km north of Sydney on November 12, 2019. A state of emergency was declared on November 11 and residents in the Sydney area were warned of "catastrophic" fire danger as Australia prepared for a fresh wave of deadly bushfires that have ravaged the drought-stricken east of the country. NEW SOUTH WALES - Fires have been continuing to rage across Australia since the weekend. Three people are dead and more than 150 homes have been destroyed. READ: Australians urged to evacuate as 'catastrophic' fires loom Fire chiefs have warned that despite cooler weather expected on Wednesday and Thursday, the danger will increase later in the week. It is claimed these are the most dangerous bushfire conditions in the country's history. The army is expected to assist in fighting the blaze and it will also deploy reserve soldiers. READ: Australian bushfires kill three, destroy at least 150 homes Hundreds of schools have been closed and entire towns evacuated as winds continue to fan dozens of existing fires across New South Wales and Queensland.